                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d35">
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Acting Secretary of State</gloss> to
                        Ambassador <persName type="to">Hengelmüller von Hengervar</persName>.</hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Department of State</hi>,<lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1906-07-19">
                            <hi rend="italic">July 19, 1906</hi>
                        </date>.</dateline>
                    <seg rendition="#left">No. 186.]</seg>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Excellency</hi>: I have the honor to acknowledge the
                    receipt of your excellency’s note No. 1002, of the 10th ultimo, communicating
                    your Government’s’ reply to the representations made by the American ambassador
                    in Vienna regarding the complaint of Mrs. Maria Horniak, otherwise Hornyak,
                    against the Hungarian authorities.</p>
                <p>A copy of your excellency’s note has been communicated, in translated form, to
                    the American ambassador in Vienna; also to the Secretary of Commerce and Labor,
                    and to Mr. John Horniak, the husband of the complainant.</p>
                <p>Accept, etc.,</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Robert Bacon.</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
